<div class="text-center">
    <h1 class="display-4">More Information about Coffee</h1>
    <p>
        Coffee, one of the most beloved beverages around the globe, 
        originates from the seeds of berries from the Coffea plant. 
        These seeds, commonly known as coffee beans, are harvested, processed, 
        and then roasted to varying degrees to achieve different flavors and 
        aromas. Whether enjoyed black or with additions like milk, sugar, or 
        spices, coffee is a versatile drink that has woven itself into the fabric 
        of daily life for many. Its invigorating properties come from caffeine, 
        a natural stimulant that helps people feel more awake and alert.
    </p>
    <p>
        The journey of coffee from bean to cup is a fascinating one. Coffee 
        beans are typically grown in the Coffee Belt, an area around the equator 
        including countries in Central and South America, Africa, and Asia. The 
        beans undergo several stages, starting with harvesting, followed by 
        processing, drying, milling, roasting, grinding, and finally brewing. 
        Each stage influences the final taste, aroma, and texture of the coffee. 
        For the curious coffee drinker, exploring different types of beans (like 
        Arabica and Robusta), various roasting profiles, and brewing methods (such 
        as French press, espresso, and pour-over) can be an exciting adventure 
        into the rich world of coffee.
    </p>
    <p>
        For those who think they already know a lot about coffee, there's always 
        more to discover. Specialty coffee culture introduces an even deeper 
        appreciation for the nuances in flavor profiles, the importance of ethical 
        sourcing, and the craft of precision brewing. Attending a coffee cupping 
        session, where you can taste and compare different coffees side by side, 
        can open up new dimensions of taste. Exploring single-origin coffees, 
        where beans are sourced from a single location rather than blended, can 
        reveal unique flavors influenced by the terroir. Even the role of barista 
        skills in the final cup's presentation and taste offers endless learning 
        opportunities. So, whether you're new to coffee or a seasoned aficionado, 
        there's always another layer of knowledge to uncover and enjoy.
    </p>
</div>